data.name: textBox1.Text
data.value: Basic lands in Magic the Gathering essentially discern between the playable colors in the game. There are five basic land types in MTG, those being White for plains, Island for Blue, Swamp for Black, Mountain for Red, and Forest for Green. Every deck in the game utilizes what is called Land, and using specific Lands they produce the given colors to show what cards they are capable of playing or what type of deck they are playing. If a player only has Islands for example they are only capable of casting spells that utilize those colors and not another color. On this same note though there are cards that are capable of being cast with any color land, and those cards are called Colorless cards. Some cards require multiple different colors to play, which we will get farther in depth into in the next section. The basic set of five lands are the typical staple for beginner play, however, there are what are called Non-Basic lands that deviate slightly from the basic five. These Non-Basic lands do a wide variety of things, but for the most part they produce multiple different colors instead of just one like the basic lands do. When using a land you turn your card to the right to tap it, which produces one Mana of that given color. Mana is what lands produce when activated and are color coded the same way as the land used to produce it.
